Installation and Environment¶

Setting up the environment:

1. install [Anaconda3](https://www.anaconda.com/distribution)
2. conda env create -f ALBA_SX.yml
3. conda activate EZ_hit-finder (source activate EZ_hit-finder)

Read in a sample .cbf image file for hit-finding parameter tweaking¶

In [46]:
cbf_file_name='/data/bioxfel/data/2018/ALBA-2018-Sep-MartinGarcia/data/Lyso2000/images/Lyso2000_17_6484.cbf'
img_array_s=fabio.open(cbf_file_name)
print('The image dimension is:',img_array_s.data.shape)
center_x=np.round(img_array_s.data.shape[0]/2).astype(np.int16)
center_y=np.round(img_array_s.data.shape[1]/2).astype(np.int16)
print('The beam center is preliminarily: (%.2f,%.2f)'%(center_x,center_y))

The image dimension is: (2527, 2463)
The beam center is preliminarily: (1264.00,1232.00)

Parameter_tweaking mode:

label_filtered_sorted,weighted_centroid_filtered,props= \
single_peak_finder(CBF_file_name,thld,min_pix,max_pix,mask_file,interact='True')
  • thld: pixel value threshold
  • min_pix: minimal number of pixels for a peak
  • max_pix: maximal number of pixels for a peak
  • mask_file: name of the mask file
  • min_peak: minimal number of peaks for a hit
In [47]:
label_filtered_sorted,weighted_centroid_filtered,props=AL.single_peak_finder(cbf_file_name,50,3,20,'None',interact='True')

Run hit-finding with tuned parameters¶

After satisfied with the parmameter tuning above in the interactive mode, we can run the hit fiding in batch mode using the optimized parameters as follows:

Usage:

ALBA_SX_uitils.py <cbf_file_list_file> <thld> <min_pix> <max_pix> <mask_file> <min_peak> <Region>
  • thld: pixel value threshold
  • min_pix: minimal number of pixels for a peak
  • max_pix: maximal number of pixels for a peak
  • mask_file: name of the mask file
  • min_peak: minimal number of peaks for a hit
  • Region: 'ALL'(full image), 'C'(central portion), 'Q'(quarter)
In [48]:

Check the output files¶

.log, eve.lst , and .pkl files are generated for each hit-fingding batch.

  • .log: log file of the hit-finding
  • eve.lst: hit event list, used for data transfer
  • .pkl: binary file consisting of the peak information, adopting Cheetah and CrystFEL convention.

Tips:¶

  1. split the .cbf file list into batches of smaller ones using "split -d ", so that multiples processes of hit-finding can be launched simultaneously.
  2. Copy only the "hits" to your hard drive, by using "rsync --files-from=*.eve.lst "
  3. Check the configuration of the computation system always, before launching multiples processes.
